Locked architectural decisions
1. Canonical trust object

The Execution Trust Record (ETR) is the authoritative record for a Business Transaction.

Every other trust artifact is associated with exactly one Execution Trust Record.

2. One Execution Trust Record per Business Transaction
Business Transaction
        │
        ▼
Execution Trust Record

The relationship is one-to-one.

3. Append-only evolution

After creation, the following collections may only grow:

overrides
executions
verifications
receipts

Existing entries are never modified or deleted.

4. Immutable core

The following fields never change after creation:

businessTransactionId
metadata
policy
signals
decision

This guarantees deterministic replay and verification.

5. Trust anchor

The Execution Trust Record is the foundation for:

Receipts
Verification
Replay
Trust Chain
Independent verification

All of these are derived from or operate against the same canonical record.

6. Cryptographic integrity

recordHash is the canonical cryptographic digest of the Execution Trust Record.

It is used to:

generate Receipts,
support independent verification,
detect tampering,
establish integrity across trust artifacts.
Canonical Principle (Locked)

The Execution Trust Record is the single source of truth for execution trust.

